76561198014277673,Not Recommended,271240,32011714,Posted: 27 May,all,Oranix,"This game... ugh.I find it hard to describe it. It seems random, but is actually very formulaic, especially in the way that the AI approaches things. Every game will play out EXACTLY the same, and if you don't do the exact things right in the exact order at the exact time, you will lose.Does not leave much room for personal playstyles or experimentation.Basically, looks good on the surface, but gets boring FAST."
76561198062719894,Recommended,271240,28194888,"Posted: 4 December, 2016",all,Studly Spud,"I have found this game to be very intricate and engaging, and have enjoyed it immensely.  I feel that most people who are disappointed with this are expecting another Civ4, set in space.  Common complaints are lack of story, short games, lack of content diversity for replaying.  However if you have the right idea about what this game is, it is amazing.  This is a fast paced competitive strategic battlefield, played with production, stock markets, and espionage, rather than armies and warfare.  Played in real time, if you sit back and try to make a happy little colony you won't last long.The very solid yet short tutorial gives you a decent understanding of a game that is easy to start, yet very tricky to master.  I have not yet ventured into competitive multiplayer.... The ""campaign"" mode is really just an extension of learning, and the skirmish or multiplayer modes are the real meat.  Every game starts much the same, and rapidly spirals off in a different direction; directly influenced by your choices and those of your opponents, with a small amount of randomised external forces.What I really appreciate about this game is the total lack of paper-scissors-rock ""counters"" that exist in most strategy games.  Everything is viable, and even if your current strategy is shut down, you can pivot to something else and still be heavily competitive from behind.  The only wrong move is inaction, however the smallest things you do will be felt elsewhere.  I wasn't fully sure what I was getting into with this game, and tbh the first couple of hours against easy AI felt shallow, however I rapidly discovered that this game is satisfyingly deep and pretty much perfect, and that the AI 'easy' level was called that for a reason.....Additionally, the strength of a game based on numbers and definite cause and effect such as this is that the AI can be intelligent, unfeeling, ruthless, efficient, and incredibly challenging.In summary; this game is darn near perfect FOR WHAT IT IS.  If you are wanting empire building, long protracted games, campaign as a main feature, then this game will not be another Civilization.  If you want short fast-paced matches in which you can test your instincts and decision making skills against opponents, while able to use a whole variety of strategy combinations, then this game will keep you happy for a long long time."
,Not Recommended,271240,19658404,"Posted: 12 December, 2015",all,generalzee,"The game is alright, but not terribly deep. A few rounds is all it takes to understand the mechanics of the game, and without a huge amount of complications it becomes very repetitive very quickly.On the bright side, the game is absolutely functional. The economy works in a way that is responsive and satisfying. Your opponents actually seem to know what they're doing (at least on harder modes). The sound and visuals are both good.On the down side the gameplay is shallow, leaving the player wanting more after a fairly short amount of time.-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------It's been a few months and the game has now come out of early access. I'm afraid that the only difference I see between the current game and the original game is Far better AI, and a nicer UI. The depth of the game hasn't been changed, and basically no new features have been added.My review remains very similar to what it was before: The game is solid in what it does, but what it does isn't all that complex, and with so few tradable items and minerals the game becomes a straight race to get Offworld Trading Companies, and flood the market. There is some nuance at the beginning depending on the map, but beyond that every game basically plays out the same."
