76561197964120751,Recommended,271240,14608953,"Posted: 23 February, 2015",all,Hyperlynx,"It's like realtime Settlers of Catan.It's not much like city builder style economic games (such as Tropico, Dwarf Fortress, Factorio, the Settlers series) because you are heavily limited by the number of tiles (ie resources) you can claim. There's no optimising your road layout because there are no roads - your cargo flies where it needs to go.The limited number of tile claims you have slows the pace from totally frantic to manageable. The game is bursts of frenetic energy and aggression as you seize an available opportunity, then back to waiting. It feels a bit like a turn based boardgame with a chess timer.I bought this game thinking I was going to have a nice quiet time building up a peaceful economy, as in the games I listed before, and that I wasn't too keen on the competitive aspect. Two hours later, I'm a cutthroat wheeling-and-dealing space CEO.That said, it's very easy to make unfixable mistakes, and the game's not much good at teaching you how to play it. I think a lot of plays will be necessary to figure out good strategies. There are also some rough edges in the game balance - there are a few ""I win"" buttons in there, which I'm expecting will get nerfed in future.It's a lot of fun, though. Just expect to think on your feet, very quickly, and to go for the throat."
,Recommended,271240,27685299,"Posted: 26 November, 2016",all,clef,"I was intimidated upon hearing about the premise of this game... It sounds like one of those games that are only fun to people with very specialized knowledge and tastes. But actually the developers have succeeded in making a very approachable and fast game about economy, business and finance, with clear tutorials and interface, and with a focus on multiplayer but still having a fun singleplayer experience.Every building needs special materials and produces something else, but all materials can be bought or sold at the market, with dynamic prices based on supply and demand. Imagine if in warcraft 2, you could sell your extra lumber to other players. There's no military combat here, but economic attacks, defense and espionage are integral to the game.You may be interested in the premise or not, but don't skip the game fearing that it will be too complicated. The mechanics are simple at the core, and may teach you an abstract thing or two about how business works in the real world."
,Recommended,271240,15534112,"Posted: 25 April, 2015",all,Apsalar,"Given the oft and loudly proclaimed provenance of this game I expected a 4X-RTS experience, except with markets instead of militaries.  I imagined hours of playing vast, sprawling games across the surface of Mars, replete with complexity and grand strategic depth.That's not what this game is.  In fact OTC is a scion of the great RTS's of the late 90s, and it operates on that same tense, refined, match-oriented, competitive level- in which the genre name becomes an anachronism, because the actual gameplay is so tight and focused that it would be best described as tactical rather than strategic.  Matches are fast-paced and relatively short, demanding a combination of quick clicks and quick thinking to stay on top.  Resources, tech, and production are all tied up with each other in a single intertangled ""tree"" of progression.  You can buy or sell any resource or product at any time if you have the money, and one of the key facets of playing well is using this ever-market to drive up the value of your surplus goods and drive down the value of your opponents', while still making sure you are keeping your levels where they need to be to avoid halts in production or debt accumulation.  There's a moment sometimes in a match where suddenly you see a way that you can make the market perform for you like a puppet- a few minutes and some well-placed clicks later and your stock is way out on top  (assuming, of course, your plans aren't deflected by your opponents' own devious machinations).  Victory in OTC occurs when one player owns all the stock of all the corporations in the match.During the best matches I experience that same sort of premium-grade thrumming that I used to get from a good game of Starcraft in college, complete with peculiar blink of bewilderment at match's end as my brain powers down its High Alert protocols and returns to normal functioning.  I find it interesting that the devs keep emphasizing how not like Starcraft this game is, and yet my gut-level experience has been very similar for the two games.  It's interesting as well that the devs were so worried about multiplayer catching on without any combat outlet for players.  And yet this game shines most brightly in the cutthroat multiplayer arena.  I think they underestimated our creativity when it comes to eradicating our opponents.  The markets of OTC can be just as disruptive and violent (and satisfying) as any zerg-infested terran marine making a bee-line for your base.Overall 7.5/10Pros:+original concept with a classic feel+elegant, streamlined gameplay+relatively short matches+rewards creativity and decisiveness+compelling soundtrackYou decide:+/-quick clicking can be a major factor in your success+/-limited options in terms of tech and production+/-the differences among the corporate classes pose some interesting market problems for players but ultimately gameplay is pretty much the same for everyone+/- Early Access...sometimes you find a diamond at the end, sometimes it's a lemon.  I do tend to trust Stardock though.+/-high tension gameplayCons:-high, inflexible price point (a side effect of Kickstarter)-graphics and glitches need a lot of work before they are polished-occasional imbalances-game doesn't prepare you for its experience (watch some LPs, it helps a lot)"
,Recommended,271240,31706009,Posted: 12 May,all,Red.Star.,"This game is definitely worth getting on sale. I read some complaints about the DLCs before buying the game. I think this is an age of DLCs. Just think about the games of Paradox -- Crusader King II is totally different with/without dlcs.  I have been watching this game for a long time. I suggest those interested buy the gold edition, for the discount you get is so far the highest.The game has a very steep learning curve. It's best to start with its tutorial and complete it with patience. And the AI will be competitive above the intern level. In SP it is possible to pause the game with space key, but not in MP. This game reminds me of the 2d classic ""capitalism"" series. That's all for now.Recommended for those who enjoys economy building and competition games."
76561198006831622,Not Recommended,271240,14522260,"Posted: 17 February, 2015",all,zannikingfool,"A brief description of this game may read ""resource management and competitive economics on Mars"" - its free from combat (at least of a gun-play kind) and runs at ""realtime"" - Sounds good (if you like that sort of thing, which I do) and faily original...BUT there is one central and perhaps critical flaw...Offworld Trading Company has some truelly fantastic and compulsive elements - it has simple yet dynamic gameplay which takes seconds to learn and forever to master; the claiming and extraction of always limited resources before your competitors is simple enough (at least in theory) - the refinement of the resources into goods that demand higher prices, none too complex - manipulating the market for your benifit needs a little practice - However, learning how and when to combine black market tricks on your competitors with manufactured price hikes that trash their stock so you can buy them at a snap -- this takes time.Sadly, time is the thing that you simply don't have.  Whilst the interface, the gameplay and the graphics are all on a scale between good and outstanding the games pacing feels all off.  It's like watching (the original) Total Recall at twenty times the normal speed; you know that there are some great moments in there that you would love to savour but it's gone before you've noticed you're enjoying yourself.  If you're victorious then it doesn't feel like you've worked for it, if you lose it dosn't feel you've had a chance to put up a fight.  A game lasts around a half an hour to an hour and moves at a pace that would give Usain Bolt jet lag...And this is worries me because I don't know how it can be changed without removing all that makes the game stand-out from the crowd.  The Unique Selling Point of this game is ""realtime"" competitive economics - but that's not strictly true; REALTIME economics is slow, careful, managed.  Sure, there is shouting and screaming on the trading floor, but the wider economic world around it moves at a more measured pace.  RTS is a format that suits combat orientated games - it's frantic ""WHO IS SHOOTING ME/WHEN DID THAT BLOW-UP!!"" quality is appropriate to its content - war is (I imagine) chaotic and frantic - it's central gameplay is built around event's that can be drawn over realtime - namely gunfights.  But if we had a TRUE RTS economics game you would need to pass it down several generations to win - Neither nation nor global corporation gained market dominance over thirty muinets, it takes hundereds of yeears.... something thats nicely communicated and simulated in the format of a turn-based game.  The question is ""who want's this game"", or perhaps rather ""When do I want this game""?  If I'm in the mood for something fast-paced but stratigic it makes sense to look for gunplay, if its long lasting and stratigic economic is better.  This has the flaw of being neither and both.In the end, for all of Offworld Trading Company's good points (and it has many), its format seems irreconcilably at odds with its content; it ain't realtime economics at all, its economics so fast it feels like you can't breath - think Arnie in the red dust with eyes about to pop."
