76561198179692627,Recommended,271240,31667033,Posted: 10 May,all,pollina,"I absolutely love this game for its uniqueness, its strategic depth, its highly compelling and competitive gameplay and its awesome community, but Offworld Trading Company is certainly not a game for everyone.  My honest recommendation for anyone who is thinking of buying it is to check out some gameplay footage first. (Zultar327, Mohawk Games, Blues OTC, philothanic, etc. all have lots of Offworld content on Youtube).Too many people buy this game thinking it is an epic, story driven city or colony builder, then end up very disappointed when they find out that the game is something else entirely. This is no Anno, Sim City or Civilization on Mars. If all you are interested in is games like those, then Offworld is most likely not the game for you.Offworld is a very unique game, which makes it very hard to explain it. It is an RTS without guns, but with lots of economic warfare. It is a bit like a digital board game played in real time. (Another reviewer once called it “Catan on steroids”, which seems oddly appropriate.) It is mostly skirmish based and very cutthroat and competitive, so don’t expect peaceful colony building. Games last 20 to 35 minutes, which is perfect for multiplayer and which makes it easy to squeeze in a game  when one has little time for gaming.Despite its fairly simple mechanics, it has a lot of strategic depth and a pretty steep learning curve. It is an RTS, but this game does not require high APM. Being good at the game is much more about observation, fast thinking and adaptation. You have to observe your opponents and the market and you always have to be prepared to adapt to what is happening on the map and in the resource and stock markets. The random map, starting prices and black market effects and your opponents’ actions will make each game play out very differently.Between AI skirmishes, a dynamic campaign mode and Daily Challenges there is a decent amount of single-player content, but multiplayer is where the game really shines. The community is one of the friendliest gaming communities out there. Despite the playerbase being fairly small, it is usually not too hard to find games. The most active time is in the European and American evening. If you have trouble finding games, I recommend to either look for Offworld multiplayer streams on Twitch and join the games there or to try and organize games via our community discord server:https://discord.gg/0pQ0rgV4DDFxO2rD"
,Not Recommended,271240,34568745,Posted: 28 August,all,Sandwichman,"Tl;dr: gameplay is mostly managing resources then the game ends with you buying someone out, or vice versa. Art ranges from great to ""wtf?"" 4/10.I think it's safe to say that they broke this game since I've last played it. And not that it was that great when I last played it, but it seemed to flow better. And the end game results felt more fair. Now, however, the resource management is all off, the way you buy shares and take over companies is completely wrong. It's like a 1st year college student's idea of what capitalism is with only wikipedia as a guide.I think they have a really interesting concept here and the graphics are great, but the execution leaves me scratching my head. If they're going to institute shares, debt, and cash, why don't they make a game around that concept..Here's how I would have done it:Debt:Your company makes purchases and creates debt. You're in the red. now other players should be able to buy that debt, and when that player pays off their debt, the other players who buy that debt get little payments (aka interest). Having more debt hurts you and helps other players and that forces you to pay it off sooner.Shares:If you're going to institute this system, then you should be able to buy and sell and have a benefit to owning them. The subsidiary option is nice, but you should be able to do more. Like short their shares, a risky move that puts you in debt and lowers their share price, just hope other players don't buy in before you do. You should also get a dividend for owning their shares.Cash: Cash should not be so weak and always running out. A good business keeps a reserve and the game just doesn't reflect that practice. Currently, the game forces you do spend spend spend to try and keep up. There is no reward or benefit to keeping cash at all.. Or at least none that I've found.Claims:In addition to buying spots of land, you should be able to buy land and speculate on the price. Surveys should be run randomly throughout the game or you should be able to pay for a survey to see if your land purchase paid off. Real estate is vastly underrepresented in this game.Resources:There are entirely too many resources and too little pay off to retrieve them. It falls into the classic RTS pitfall of ""Not enough minerals,"" and needs balancing. Resources are traded in the game, which is good, but they're handled poorly. Other than grabbing what you need to build stuff, there is little benefit to owning that tiny bit more than you need. And the compensation is just too weak to try and be a part of it. For example, if you dominate a resource and have a near monopoly, you should be able to gouge prices. Instead the game's resources system just magically lowers the value of said resource until you're left with 300+ useless units that you can't offload.Black Market, Pirates, powerups, patents, hackers, and so on and so on... and other buildings:What a mess. Basically it's options overkill. This needs to be streamlined and cut down to the base items.Overall gameplay:You'd have to completely rip apart the current game to get where I'm going with this, but basically there needs to be a focus on 1. Colonization, 2. Business, and 3. ""specials"" (aka, actionable things people can do to spice the game up). Basically the game now is 1. Resources 2. Resources 3. More resources, but now you sell them so you buy someone out or get bought out. It sucks.But back to my review. This game needs a ton of work to feel more like a game, because right now it feels like resource manager 2017. Also the company representative art is like Portland food truck indie art and feels completely off. If it weren't for that, the game graphics would be near perfect as I really like the game's assets. Oh and before I forget, the tutorial is about 500 paragraphs too long. You can teach the gameplay and add a little story, but not the other way around. As it stands now there are about 10 screens for each thing you build. ""so you want to build a metal mine, eh? well first you have to know my name, where I'm from and hey look at my sick food truck tattoos..."" It's painful to read.I haven't been able to get the enjoyment I had when this game was in early access which is a shame because I was looking forward to the finished product. Which, if you can't tell already, is not where this game is right now. 4/10."
