76561198025626647,Recommended,271240,14440886,"Posted: 12 February, 2015",all,dltarex,"Early Access Review (2/12/15)BLUF: #1 - I feel that RTS is a poor term to describe this game and #2 - from the Devs “Feedback! We want to know how players are going to break the game, suss out any degenerate strategies, and make sure we polish every rough edge off of the gameplay. Offworld Trading Company is fully funded; we are not relying on Early Access sales to finish the game.” This statement is key.***For those of you who have been burned by early access games before please take the note from the Devs seriously. This is a very playable and stable game right now and they already have the resources to put the finishing touches on it. So you are not really paying to make the game, you are getting an early shot at the game and a chance to drive further balance into the system. The final quality of this game will depend heavily on balancing the PVP aspects of the game so the more feedback they have now the better.As far as this being a RTS; while it might be the closest term we have to define it, that will give many people the wrong idea. There are no units to move, no combat, and no chokepoints. You establish a base and build buildings to harvest resources (much like the Warhammer:Dawn of War series) and use those resources to develope higher teir commdities to eventually sell for cash and buy out your opponents. It is fast paced and at times will feel like a RTS, but traditional RTS tactics will fail for the most part.The key is that the prices that determine which resource is the 'win' resource will depend on the strat adapted by the players in the game and will change from game to game. There are no Ultimate Resources that win the game each time. The higher teir products will usually have a higher price, but if everyone in that game chases them then the price will plummet and the player sitting on a pile of low teir resources can dominate. Basically the L33T strat that everyone wants to use will neuter itself before it can win.My current concerns:The pace of the game is very aggressive for a strategy game. The pace can be adjusted and I have only played against the AI with their GHz brains, but knowing PVP types this could quickly devolve into a 'who can spam out the first 3 correct buildings' contest.The interface needs to do a better job of letting the player know whats going on. There are some pretty nasty things lurking on the Black Market and all you get is a chat box type readout to announce them and maybe an onscreen animation if you happen to be looking at that part of the map at the time. The trick is to find the balance where we get the info we need without getting our screen spammed out by alerts. Good luck Mohawk!"
,Recommended,271240,14441257,"Posted: 12 February, 2015",all,Hobbes,"Ignore the entry ticket price, this is one of the most polished Early Access titles you'll ever see.Offworld Trading Company, possibly the most curious of creatures. A game that dares to break the rules, it's not quite a 4x and it's not quite an RTS, and yet it's got elements of both, as well as a very brutal and brilliant introduction into capitalism in it's most true sense.The creator of this was the lead designer of Civ IV, still widely regarded as the pinnacle of the series and still very much fondly remembered by many to this day (and often still played by many, it's got a dedicated following, mods and glorious goodies, it's still fantastic, if you don't have Civ IV, please get it). He's brought a very unique approach to this game and has effectively talen the spirit of M.U.L.E. and brought it back, shaken it up and presented us with a entirely new set of concepts to learn and re-learn.The game plays out over a martian map, randomly generated from various landscapes made up of craters, dried riverbeds and valleys that do a fairly solid impression of conveying the martian scene, as well as various terrain that can be covered in ice, certain areas will be marked with resource node icons indicating they are of potential exploitative value for various minerals.  Arranged on a hex grid, you'll immediately be put in mind of old strategy games, but the comparison ends there. There are no units to control, at all. You only build things.A non combat 4X, is this even possible? Say whaaaaaaaaaat?Yes. I'll repeat that. You only build things. In this game, your structures are your units in effect. Your mines, your colony buildings, and your economy represents your ""arsenal"" and ""weaponry"". This makes for a frenetic early game as everyone jumps into the map blind, all arriving at the starport with nary but a blank map and the ability to scan in a limited range and for a limited number of times (these recharge over time, but you're effectively capped to a number of 'hops'), you'll see tantalising highlights on the horizon suggesting possible mineral nodes, but you won't KNOW what they are unless you scan right over them.This presents the first risk/reward mechanic, because the very early stages are a gold rush, do you take your time and map out the area, performing a thorough survey and pick the best spot (and risk losing it by accident to a lucky colonist) or do you jump at the first spot that ""looks good"" and risk sacrificing a better opportunity later on?During the early game, you'll be moving fairly quickly to make the optimal use of your initial claims, working out the best places to put down mines, whether you're best off setting up colony infrastructure or buying in the resources you need whilst you export minerals, again, these are all choices you have to balance, and the economics are very fluid. The game operates an exceptionally liquid supply and demand based market that fluctuates very quickly based on what is sold and what is required by the people off planet, so taking advantage of peaks in the market, and stocking up when there's a glut can make for excellent trading strategies on top of the usual manufacturing gigs.As the game progresses you'll be offered auctions on patents, black market goods, pirates will offer their services, and the game settles into a reasonable pace, it's not too brisk that you'll be panicking over keypresses, and you'll usually have more than enough time to plan your moves, but it's juuuust fast enough that you'll not start feeling bored or that there's a lull in the action. The pace even now feels just right, and the game even at this Early Access stage feels amazingly well refined. The AI is also brutal, which makes for some excellent and tense singleplayer matches (and if you're not careful, amazingly short ones, the AI knows when to strike and buy you out, with scary precision).The economy has a solid enough set of gears that you can work through as you expand, moving up through basic goods at first, and then you can decide to diversify, thus preventing your company from becoming exposed to the fluctuations or even possible manipulations of the market, or you can specialise in luxury goods, with the aim of striking it rich when demand is at it's highest. If, and it's a big if, you do this well, the rewards are huge, and in an RTS, would be the equivalent of nuking the base, here you win with money. Earn more than your opponent, buy them out and crush them.This is where the true nature of the game comes to the fore, as a lesson in future capitalism, it's bold, and even at times cruel, but perhaps a very good mirror to hold up and show what can happen if the only guiding force is the market, as a game, this makes it a brilliant and unique concept, and as an Early Access product, well, it's far from ""Early"" in my eyes. This game feels very much close to completion, they're more talking about fleshing out the multiplayer, getting the pacing and balancing just right and layering on the polish (this game needs polish?!?! WHERE?). Truth be told, it feels very polished as it is, there's a few graphical glitches but these are -minor-.Yes, the cost of entry is high, but for once, this is a game that actually justifies the entry fee.Closing thoughtsThis is a rare case where Early Access actually is a literal application of the term, you're paying to get Early Access to the almost complete product, and to provide feedback that helps shape it before it goes to the final version. Balancing, tweaking, and providing strategic insight to the developers, who have been listening and responding, and watching in kind.It's a very good example of how Early Access in a ""shortform"" approach should work (there's plenty of longer form SEA games that have done well such as Prison Architect, but that's a seperate discussion). As a result I really have little hesitation putting the paws up for this one, it's a genuinely brilliant game and it brings something different to the table, which it should be commended for.Current verdict :Highly recommended, and ignore the Early Access sticker, there's nothing Early about this game, it's very much in an end-to-end playable state"
76561197972500727,Not Recommended,271240,21912475,"Posted: 18 March, 2016",all,Binford,"This game needs a lot of work to make it enjoyable. The Black Market items just make the game stressful as, if you're the highest ranked player for the mission, you will inevitably be targeted repeatedly by the other three AI players, making it nearly impossible to manage your resources. Even if you are doing really well and own all the stock in your own company in a skirmish, another player can still somehow buy stock in your company that shouldn't even be for sale and win the game. The claim system is completely hampering the ability to play the game as it is portrayed in the videos. There's just too small of a map and too limited of resources to enjoy the act of building up a company or colony. The missions are over so quickly I feel no satisfaction even if I win.Yes, most RTS's are military games, but there is an econmic angle to them as well. The strongest economies are usually the winners. This game substitutes the lack of tanks and turrets for Black Market items that blow up buildings, temporarily disable them or capture them for other players. THIS IS NO DIFFERENT. There is no difference between this game and a military RTS except that this game is not fun, not realistic in the aspects of building up a company or the ability to focus on a single resource chain / manufacturing process, and it is over so quickly it leaves you wondering why you just spent 30-45 minutes playing a ""week"" mission in a compaign that makes you start all over again the next week with some ""upgraded"" capabilities.I spent one skirmish (because I wanted to play with all available buildings) only to find that by the time that I could start launching items into space for selling offworld (the best way to make money in the game by far) that the other computer player had already bought out the other two companies (which I had bought stock in, but could no longer as they were now 'subsidiaries' of the main company) and proceeded to blow up my only launchpad (because, again, limited building claims) with the black market dynomite option even though it was protected with the Goon Squad (the only defensive measure in the game that you have to continually and immediately purchase after each attack [which is an extremely ridiculous option considering the computer can repeatedly attack you faster than you can click to purchase and place your defense against this).Maybe I haven't given this game enough time to understand it completely, but, as an experienced gamer of RTS's. I found this game difficult to understand, unintuitive in controls and concepts, not fun (for previously mentioned reasons), and regretted buying it immediately.Hopefully this game has a major overhaul by the time it goes into full version, but I will not be playing it again and hope that I get my refund."
76561198159404653,Recommended,271240,31675620,Posted: 10 May,all,TheProphet,"NOTE: If you're looking for a Civilization-like game, do NOT buy Offworld: it is in no way similar to Civ games, and should not be judged as such. I highly recommend looking up streams or recent gameplay videos if you're unsure about what OTC is, or if you'd enjoy it.I'd also like to point out that I only play a fraction of what OTC has to offer, therefore the following thoughts are based only on 1v1 matches, both ranked and singleplayer. There are also 4 player ranked matches, up to 8 player lobbies and singleplayer equivalents, as well as a large amount of other singleplayer content that I have yet to try.Offworld is an economic RTS--not a Turn-Based game--that manages to deliver an incredible amount of depth in relatively short matches (typically 10-30 minutes, which I understand is short for the genre). With that depth; however, comes a respectably steep learning curve. Keep this in mind whilst reading less-than-40-hour reviews that claim Offworld has no depth and is repetitive to the point that you've seen it all after just a few hours of gameplay.I am of the opinion that 20-50 hours of gameplay is necessary just to have a firm grasp on how the game works, and is hardly enough time to give an accurate appraisal of replay value. For me at 110 hours played, I still feel as if this review is premature, but I can tell you that depth is not lacking from my perspective.Where does the depth come from?Players must adapt to a host of varying conditions including the maps themselves, starting resource prices, a neutral colony that adds recource demand (and supply in some cases), random events, and perhaps most importantly: the actions of other players. That last point is where the multiplayer side of Offworld really shines, and while the AI is respectable, it is never going to offer the same gameplay experience that human opponents will. As I said previously, my experience in single player modes is limited, so I cannot accurately comment on the campaign; however, standard singleplayer games have certainly been a help in preparation for multiplayer ranked matches, and still serve as a training tool in my relatively young Offworld career.Currently, there are four different player factions to choose from, and two locations (Mars and Ceres); there is an expected increase to six factions, and three locations with the first major expansion Jupiter's Forge arriving some time this spring. Expansion aside, I expect the base game alone would be enough to hold my interest for hundreds of hours, and I repeat: I'm only playing one of the ranked modes available, and the mode I don't play (4 player FFAs) is preferred by most players and is certainly the more complicated of the two.If that type of depth sounds intriguing to you, I strongly encourage watching some gameplay footage to make sure Offworld is what you think it is. I overdid the research part, and spent at least a couple dozen hours watching tournament footage, and gameplay streams before making the purchase, but I don't regret buying Offworld in the slightest.There are a number of negative reviews left by people who evidently were not aware of Offworld's basic premise before buying. Offworld is the perfect game for the right person, just take a few extra minutes and make sure you're that person rather than another disappointed reviewer that was hoping for a different game."
76561198066543156,Not Recommended,271240,28189669,"Posted: 4 December, 2016",all,paradigm87,"Although this game provides a new concept and looks interesting, to me its replayability was quite low. Seeing the current price tag I believe this price is way too high for the little content the game provides."
,Recommended,271240,31213978,Posted: 18 April,all,Benson,"As far as RTS / resource management games go, this one is quite the doozy. Most games give you three or four resources to manage and figure out, this one throws about a dozen at you. The tutorials are engaging, the game is visual beautiful, you'll find yourself getting sucked into the old ""just one more match..."" cycle.Having said all that...The AI in single player games is STUPIDLY overpowered. You'll find yourself beat to the punch on literally every single thing you try to do. Some of the various factions (okay, really just the Science HQ) are so oddly configured that it's almost impossible to figure out.This game is unforgiving and has a super steep learning curve, but if you're okay with all of that, I'll give it a solid 8/10 stars."
76561197970289083,Not Recommended,271240,14476936,"Posted: 14 February, 2015",all,shiremct,"As many other reviewers of this game have stated, the price point of this game is simply way too high for what you get, especially considering the game is in early access and I expect them to only raise the price from here. I don't shy away from early access games and I've had more than a few that never really progressed as I hoped/expected, but most I feel I at least get my money's worth out of them, but at $35, this is one of the few I definitely regret picking up.It's not really a bad game and it is an interesting concept, but the sacrifices the developers have made to make matches fit into 20-30 minutes have made the gameplay chaotic and often times inconsistent... not things that are typically appreciated in an economic game, competitive real-time or not. It also lacks any decent mechanisms to defend yourself from sabatoge or simply being bought out once the bulk cash transactions start coming in in the late game, so winning or losing a match can be both frustrating and unsatisfying. You can carefully manuever yourself into an advantageous position to corner a market on a resource or disrupt an opponent's supply chain but then you get 75k from one offworld shipment of a base resource like oxygen, dump all your resources on the market, and hit a + button a couple times and win without any of it mattering.The game definitely lacks depth and each match usually hinges completely on the base materials like glass or power. Regardless of which resources are the focus on any given match, the gameplay is mostly the same every time. It can be fun and it does have potential if the developers are open to some design changes, but it is simply not worth $35 or more right now and I seriously doubt it ever will be.I would love to be wrong and see great things happen for this game as development continues, but right now, I can not recomment it."
,Recommended,271240,14462948,"Posted: 14 February, 2015",all,Zebulan,"I recommend this game, with a grain of salt!  This is not a game for everyone and the price point isn't for everyone, either.The description reads that the game is complete and only looking to do polish and balancing.  In my eyes, the game is not complete, and shouldn't be deemed complete.  For $40 CAD, Offworld Trading Company will make your chequebook scream.  The sheer lack of content in this game at present doesn't make this feel like a $40 game; however, this may be the ""spoiled adult"" in me talking - It cost more to buy M.U.L.E. for the C64 back in the day, and it has far less.For starters, everyone fights for the same resources, to produce the same few marketable goods.  This is, of course, the entire premise of the game, but I don't feel it's done correctly.  The game really boils down to ""Who clicks faster.""  You have the same relative strategy among all the other players, no matter the race you play: Build necessary starting materials to upgrade your HQ, buy materials that are dirt cheap and sell materials that are pricey.  The lack of materials and race specializations may be the downfall here, because once you fall behind the competition, winning becomes unattainable.  Since everyone is fighting for the same resources, whoever dominated the market first, wins; you may as well just resign.You are given dirty underhanded tricks to try and slow down the competition, with ever increasing cost as they are used.  That, in itself, is another problem.  The profiteer gets to use these features to their hearts content - they're making the money, after all.  As they use these features against you to continue pushing themselves ahead, the underhanded tricks end up costing more - something you obviously cannot afford - putting the balance in the hands of the first place position.You may be wondering, ""Wow, he's whining a lot about losing a game!"" and no, I've won my fair share, both against the A.I. and humans; I write this from both perspectives.  If you get ahead of someone, you literally can continue to open the gap between yourself and second place, just because I landed on that Iron first.  I truly did not find the game enjoyable when I was trouncing my competition; it was far more fun when we were on equal footing, needing to make quick decisions to outwit each other.I still give this game a positive recommendation.  After all is said and done, I very much enjoyed myself playing Offworld Trading Company in its current state.  I cannot say I will ever play it again though, which is why the $40 price tag seems extremely steep.  This is one of those games that you will love to play a lot and never play again.  As much as I would love to launch it in future, after having figured out ""how to win,"" the game has lost all flavour due to its extreme lack of content.Should the developers revisit the economy and add an abundance more resources, giving all players a chance to compete, then I feel this would be an exceptional real-time strategy game.  Until then however, this is a game of it's own genre: Real-time clicking competition."
,Recommended,271240,22757438,"Posted: 2 May, 2016",all,Dipex,"There is a really strong caveat in recommending this, which is that the tags on the store page are extremely deceptive.  This is not an economic game, this is not a simulation game, this is not a trading game, and this is not a base building game.  This is a very fast paced, micro-intensive RTS.Its an interesting take on the RTS genre, because you don't have any units to control.  But make no mistake, this game plays very similarly to one of the micro practice maps for SC2, and uses essentially the same skillset.  Its just that instead of microing units around a map, you're constantly scanning the map, spamming abilities, and hitting the buy/sell button.  I know it may sound like this is fundamentally different from microing units around, but in practice its not.If you're someone who likes the micro game in SC2, you'll like this game.  If you're a more casual RTS player then this probably isn't the game for you.There's nothing wrong with that, and the game itself is quite well done, but the game is definitely targetted towards a relatively small niche and the store page/reviews in no way reflect that."
,Recommended,271240,33492790,Posted: 12 July,all,Toast,"I am so glad that this game exists. With so many RTS's out there trying to be AoE or something along the lines of Civilization, this game dares to be different, and even if you don't like it, you can at least agree with that.Offworld Trading Company is an RTS that instead of being based around fortification and combat, is based around economics, and it works so well!Admittedly when I first started playing this game, I thought it was going to be a bit slow and tedious. But that was before I started campaign mode. The devs have made the stakes so perfectly weighted in this game that anything can feel rewarding whether it be winning the campaign or coming second on one of the rounds. And the sheer speed of some of the rounds can knock you flat on your butt. You'd think that buying and selling iron and silicon would be the most boring premise of a game but the way it's set up, it feels like your life depends on an opponent buying a little bit of carbon from you.For anyone who would be deterred from the idea of never actually fighting your opponents, I suggest you give this game a shot. It may not provide the exact same feeling as toppling the final wall of your friend's base, but it'll give you an amazing rush when you screw everyone over by having a monopoly on food."
76561198137744303,Recommended,271240,28542378,"Posted: 22 December, 2016",all,Spry_Fly,"I bought this on the recent sale, and it is easily worth the full price for any strategy game lover. Where to start? I feel like I have to explain first, and foremost, what this game actually brings to the table. I am a lover of RTS and the turn-based strategy staples. I am also a lover of MOBA type multiplayer. I think it is important to note that the single player and multiplayer are almost two different games. They follow the same mechanics, but the single player feels almost like a career-mode where matches are linked together and unlocking perks for your chosen CEO along the way, while the multiplayer brings the most intense purely competitive gameplay that I have seen in years. Even in the games where I get trounced I am left feeling like I have more grasp on the game than before, and know this is a benefit for future games.The reason this game is amazing to me is that there isn't a ""meta"" strategy to just win. This game requires a fluid strategy with the goal being to acquire competing companies by buying a majority stake. The goal is to develop supply chains that produce goods from basic to higher tier products made out of those base resources. One players actions in the first minute may require a fundamental shift in the strategy of another. This is way more than the generic paper-rock-scissors we see in a lot of strategy games, or simply any competitive game.This brings us to the learning curve. If you have played a strategy game before 2000 then the tutorial is amazingly informative. For those new to the RTS genre (I see this game mostly as such), it will feel unfair to lose repeatedly at first. These losses are the growing process of grasping the mechanics. As you start you will realize you have been handed a toolbox with a dozen tools, and winning only comes when you know the time and place to use each tool. You will lose suddenly and realize that you simply forgot about one aspect, but the oversight is just one more learning opportunity. Players that go into a situation saying I want to always use this specific company faction or believe they have an infallible one-size-fits-all strategy will lose, and quickly at that.I have seen reviews where the reviewers say that the game is about speed and not strategy. The speed simply comes with playing and understanding the resources needed for expansion. Again for RTS players think of the first time you grasped how to expand bases quickly to reach end game in the likes of Warcraft, C&C, AoE. Once you know how to upgrade quickly then it is time for strategy to kick in. The tutorial games are difficult at first, but only because the learning curve of these levels want you to graduate with the knowledge of the mechanics before letting you loose.The multiplayer wait times can be on the long side for FFA(4-player) matches, but the game allows you to do the 'Daily Challenge' scenario or a skirmish against the AI while you wait. That game will be autosaved before entering the multiplayer match. 1v1 matches have much shorter wait times. I think 1v1 is easier (may be different for each person), but FFA is where the real fun lies.If you like single player more than Patron DLC is a must (adds aspects to campaign mode), and I think the Ceres DLC is definitely worth it as well (adds new resources, new power supply, new map type).TL;DR:Anyone that wants to be in control of their own game strategy on the fly in quick, highly competitive matches with RTS elements must own this game. A lot of gamers lately want their hand held by a cut-and-paste guide that will ensure they win a high amount of the time. Thankfully this is not that game, this game requires one to like facing challenges.Edit: I'm now over 115 hours in, and this review was from about 15 hours in. I had only seen the tip of the iceburg. This game continues to amaze and I am still learning more with every game 100 hours later."
