,Recommended,271240,16623514,"Posted: 22 June, 2015",all,Viishnahn,"Offworld Trading Company™–Competitive Market StrategyRating:RecommendedFor young aspiring entrepreneurs, Earth has grown much too crowded to do business. The vast openness of the barren planet Mars calls to explorers and investors alike. Once the colonies have been established, the entrepreneurs see the potential for profit. Businesses start popping up on the Red Planet – this is where you come in.Offworld Trading Company is a fast-paced strategy game all about manipulating the Martian market, producing goods and buying out other businesses. Natural resources are limited and competition is brutal for control of the richest veins. Placement of mines, extractors, and other resource-producing buildings is critical to amassing enough materials to purchase new structures, upgrade your headquarters and get more claims. Each claim allows you to place one structure – use them wisely.Price values of the thirteen types of resources fluctuates with market activity. Is someone selling off their entire aluminum stash? Expect to see prices nosedive. You can also buy stock in your opponents’ companies. If all stock gets purchased and you have enough money, you can buy them out, causing all their buildings to come under your control. The goal of the game is to be the last man standing by buying out all your opponents.The only bad points this game has so far are its high retail price ($40) and the black market feature. The black market in this game makes investing in buildings risky. Found a high (level 3) water deposit? Someone can purchase an Underground Nuke for a paltry $1000 - $3000 to knock that deposit down to low (level 1)permanently. It seems an unnecessary element in an already risky business environment.I haven’t explored deep into this game, still in Early Access at this point, but it’s been both challenging and rewarding. You may ask “Is it really worth $40 in Early Access?” No. Wait forat least25% off, preferably 50% or more. If you’re a dedicated economy gamer (Railroad Tycoon, Capitalism series), this might trip your trigger. Pick it up if it goes on sale.Not RecommendedRecommended with Caution- RecommendedHighly RecommendedRecommended as Essential"
,Recommended,271240,22872700,"Posted: 8 May, 2016",all,nacon,"Offworld is a unique RTS game that captures the best and worst parts of capitalism, in space! I've been following this game for some time, and I am not disappointed by the results of the hard work of the development team.The overall objective of the game is to become the most profitable off-world trading company by becoming the most profitable and efficient corporation around. You'll achieve this by building supply chains of goods, selling them to a local colony, shipping them off the planet, and using your gains to buyout your competitors while avoiding being bought out yourself.Positives:+Amazing soundtrack by Christopher Tin (composer of Baba Yetu, of Civ 4 fame)+Quick cutthroat gameplay; the decisions on where to land, and what to start producing are the beginnign of a race to quickly provide goods that meet the demands of a local colony.+The gameplay is unique: there isn't any 'militay' component to this game; instead you will be competing with other corporations in the marketplace to become the most efficient and profitable offworld-trading company.+Interesting hostile actions - while you can play it straight and just compete on the 'free market', there are a variety of options to sabatoge your competitors through illicit means.+Unique factions  - each faction has their own set of strengths, and weaknesses; playing one versus another feels very interesting and different.+Great writing (in the tutorial and opening missions, at any rate).Negatives:-It seems like there's not really a comeback mechanic once you start to fall behind; if you make a few mistakes early, you're probably going to have a bad time. I could be wrong, but once I start to lose, I continue to lose.-The factions aren't visually all that different.-This game is probably overpriced for the content that you're getting; I recommend purchasing this game on at least a 25% sale, probably closer to 50%.-I'm unsure about the replayability of the game; so far, the experience has been novel; outside of multiplayer, I don't think the game will provide more than 20 horus of gameplay.Overall, I highly recommend this game for RTS players who want a different experience - namely one that focuses on competitive supply chains and economic efficiency. The game has a lot of character, and has been very enjoyable to explore."
,Recommended,271240,18022603,"Posted: 13 September, 2015",all,Eneregor,"I was interested in this game since it was announced and I can safely say it is everything I wanted it to be. The AI is incredible, constantly buying and destroying buildings to account for changes in the market. I can only imagine what complex algorithms are driving these decisions. If the AI isn't cheating, then the developers must be geniuses. Thanks for this awesome game, I can't wait to see it finished. Too bad it is a bit under-the-radar.The only changes I wish to see made are to the stock market. Currently it is not worth it to sell stocks because the stock is worth more than the sell price. Stock market trading needs to be more strategic rather than just a button you click when you want to beat another player. Players should be encouraged to invest in other players, possibly by removing the penalty for selling a stock and by removing the stock boost when you buy a stock. This way I can invest in a player early on, then sell the stocks and turn a fair profit later."
