,Recommended,271240,14452442,"Posted: 13 February, 2015",all,Zane Thanatos,"Overall, somewhat suprised and pleased with the game. I'm still not terribly happy with the price point (I think for EA something around $20 would be more fair with a possible $30-$35 point when the game is finished) but I don't think I wasted my money.Some of my negative comments first:- The UI can be a bit clunky and laggy at points.- If you leave a campaign game in the middle you seem to automatically lose that round (no way to save it and return later unless I'm being oblivious).- If you start losing rounds in the campaign it becomes extremely difficult to make up the lost ground.- No clear indication of when a campaign is over/ability to have multiple campaigns going at once.My biggest takeaway - no problems with the gameplay. The rounds definetly go by quicker then I thought they would as do the campaigns. I do wish there was an option in the campaign to vary the number of starting opponents (simply because once they are all eliminated you win and they can get eliminated fairly quickly) but thats fairly minor. The AI is extremely robust and even the start of the game takes some thought (eg do you drop your base quickly and move to what nodes you can see, do you spend longer scanning hoping to hit the motherload, etc). It does feel like it's really all just a race to the offworld markets (they are so lucrative that whoever gets their first is more or less going to win the game) but the gameplay itself is great. The game takes some forethought as you are limited in what you can do via a limited number of claims (it would be nice if you yourself could give up or auction off a claim). Graphics overall are simple (but clean) and make it extremely easy to see what is going on in-game.All in all I still do have a bit of an issue recommending it at this price point but if you think you'd happen to like the genre and aren't tight with cash I would pick the game up. Hopefully this turns into a good example of Early Access but even if we never heard another word from the Devs the game is completely playable now.Edit: After playing some more I do have to say there are some annoying balance issues (some of the ""races"" are clearlier to play/win with then others and some of the abilities/techs are way to strong while others are almost useless) but hopefully those will be addressed going forward."
,Recommended,271240,14481473,"Posted: 15 February, 2015",all,Etheras,"I've been following this game since before it was on Steam. Such a great concept! And it does not disappoint.The Good* Simple game mechanic that grows to a complex interconnected system* Easy to learn, requiring almost no tutorial, but difficult to master* Fun and addictive gameplay* A lot of the usual grind has been automated, leaving the player almost entirely grind-free to focus on base management (yay). The sole exception is the Saboteur system, which you can find in ""The Bad"" section below.* Challenging AI* Very satisfying victories without long drawn-out endgames* Decent graphics (if a bit blocky)* I am playing this in early-access, and yet the game seems full-featured and stable.* Interesting and current topic (mars colonization)* Well thought-out in terms of resources, resource usage, and gameplay mechanics* Offword mining and its actually about (mostly) peaceful commerce? What an original idea!The bad* The core game mechanic involves getting resources first, and then combining/upgrading to extract them faster. Other than avoiding pirate raids, no thought is given to logistics. I would have liked some road or train building, or having to run power lines or pipelines, rather than everything being delivered via hover selds* The sabotage system is annoying and feels ""taped on"". Its mostly ineffective, and yet pulls the player away from base management. Especially towards the end of the campaign, this can get kind of grindy... with players always having to repair or re-up their goon-squad, and keep track of attacks all over the place* The first colony almost always wins - I suppose that's incentive to drop early, but with a pausable interface, all the level3 resources near the colony are gone by the time the second corporation touches down* The game seems weighted towards Expansionist and Saboteur factions, with little real benefit for the robots or scientists* Synth voices for the characters are annoyingNot sure if these are good or bad...* I feel like there should be more of a sandbox mode, perhaps with some far-future constructions like terraformers?* Game is also quite short. It seems like a perfect length for what this game is. However, its a lot of fun, and I kinda hope it gets more features, which (I think) would need a longer campaign* Its cliche, but I expected at some point to find alien ruins / fossils / alien tech, but didn't. This could go either way. It adds a bit of mystery and alien-ness, and deepens a story.. but it is very typical and overdone too.ConclusionLoved it. I love strategy and simulation games, so this might get a touch of extra appreciation from me that might not be shared by all. Even so, I'd give Offword Trading Company a 9.5 / 10.Thanks for reading!"
76561198026913459,Recommended,271240,14440724,"Posted: 12 February, 2015",all,troublmaker,"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eSc9IG8ywxQUpon loading up the game I was surprised to find that despite the early access tag, it's actually a full game with polish.The game is sort of similar to Civ in that it is a 4x, but that's where the comparisons will end. It's closer to an economic simulator. You build infrastructure that produces resources. Resources can be used to produce new infrastructure. Infrastructure can take resources and created finished products out of them. And with all that you can sell them out to a dynamic market in which the price will fluxuate based on how much each player is selling of that commodity.The main part of the game is surviving as a company and buying out other ones. If your company value falls low you become vulnerable to losing shares of your company to competitors. Your company value is your debt and your infrastructure value combined. So paying off debt will make it harder for people to buying you, while having a large sum will allow you to buy an opponent.Once you have bought an opponent you gain their stuff in full and gain a significant advantage.The game comes with a tutorial for playing the game and playing each of the four factions. Each faction comes with its own unique set of opening boosts and needs. With a few dozen maps to choose from there is tonnes of gameplay value for your dollar.Fans of games like Port Royale, Rise of Venice, Anno 2070, and C.E.O. should definitely give this game a try. For people who are newer to economic simulators and want to give it a try, this might be the game for you."
