,Not Recommended,271240,22816108,"Posted: 5 May, 2016",all,golan,"[Intro] Had a bit of difficulty deciding between yay or nay, gave it a bit of consideration. The idea is interesting and not explored enough, so I felt very tempted to recommend solely on the premise of having a more diverse RTS scene. The decision rested on how they delivered on what they tried to achieve and promised.[Justification]It's not an interesting RTS (though i might be proven wrong if in a couple of years we see this game played competively, which I doubt). The way it is now, you'll have a difficult time playing on the higher levels until you find exploits that break the game. You won't become good at gaming an interesting rulset against an interesting opponent, you'll try to become good at beating the way the game was designed.Is not well balanced out and doesn't have an interesting AI, though people who might like '90s ""challenging"" (punishing) AI might want to give this a go for all times sake.The difficulty levels are simple starting penalties, which shows how little good gameplay is ""rewarded"" the player who makes the least mistakes wins, it should be more than that and I can't see it.There are 4 factions you can play as, they're not symetrical, but not well balanced out for asymetrical gameplay either (and they're not all that different). The robotic faction seems to be the obvious choice at the moment, the rest that are introduced later to the player will make your own playthrough more and more difficult, not different. Why would one not choose the faction that offers the easiest win when playing a skirmish match? Disclaimer: I caped at medium difficulty. I don't feel motivated to continue learning the game to beat the game.The economics. Aah, this should have been what made the game. Does the game make some interesting commentary about economics in RL, in video games or gives us an interesting mechanic through which the player might learn something useful about how economy works? No, none of these. The game uses very basic supply/demand system to set dynamic prices, which is cool as an idea. But there's no background simulation of why these resources are really needed, the demand is neither believable and allows for fluctuations which are actually based on supply alone and RNG demand. Boooooring.This is one of the objective reasons why one may argue that the game has no depth.[Others] Many talked about the price. I agree, it's too expensive for what it has to offer. I played the game and don't plan on purchasing content for the game. However, I wanted to avoid this and focus on how well the game delivers what it set out to accomplish. I'm also annoyed with the low res textures, gimmickey animation, almost like in a facebook game (though many liked the style for some reason). The campaign doesn't offer any compelling backstory, it just allows you to experience what the game has to offer a little bit more gradually.[TL;DR] The game has an interesting idea, but it's not very well delivered. It's worth trying out, but then you have to consider if it has enough value to offer to you."
