,Recommended,271240,25257076,"Posted: 30 August, 2016",all,Terror Incognita,"Okay, so I'm going to put the important bit first. If you're a fan of the RTS genre, but you dislike the intensity of the micro required to perform in the genre at a high level competitively,this is the game for you.Don't even read the rest of the reviews; just buy it and prepare for a fantastic experience.Offworld Trading Company is adeepgame. A very deep game. What you need to succeed is an ability to accurately assess a given situation, and make good decisions based on other players' actions. That's pretty much it. The difficulty comes with how many variables there are: buildings, resources, money, debt, the black market, and other players. These variables interact in many ways, but never through direct conflict.It's pretty clear that the inspiration behind OTC was board gaming, and there are ways in which it feels like a board game at times. But computers are capable of more calculations than humans which, coupled with the fact that so much thought has gone into the intricacies of the economic system, makes building an economic empire both very rewarding and enormously fun.Multiplayer is balanced extremely well. All of the game-breaking exploits have been quashed by this point, and watching streams of the very best players makes it apparent that it's careful consideration of options, and not raw APM, that's rewarded in this game. This fact alone makes it almost unique within the genre, and as a result I can't recommend this game highly enough. There are enough active players in the ranked queues at the time of writing that you'll pretty much always get a game, and that will be improved further when you (yes,you!) buy it and start playing. So off you go.Oh, and the guy who made it is the guy who made Civilization IV, which is the best Civ game to date by a long way. He knows how to make games."
,Recommended,271240,31702400,Posted: 12 May,all,2flow,"Probably my favorite RTS of all time. Whereas most RTS's seem to be just about who can spam the most units out first and zerg rush the other base, Offworld is a bit trickier. You have to learn when and where to build your base, what resources to rush, and when to rush them. You have to learn to watch your enemies closely and interfere when neccesary. Watch what they build and do your best to counter them. There's a market running alongside all of this, which your decisions influence heavily. If everyone ends up building electronics, they'll come down in price, and no one will be happy. Racing to build capital can become pretty intense, especially when you're watching your stocks slowly get bought out by your enemies. There's also a fun black market you can use to throw a wrench in everyone else's plans. A well-timed EMP can turn the game around.That said, your first few games could be frustrating. It takes a few rounds to learn the pros and cons of different bases, the ebb and flow of the market, when to build extra amenities or not. And without having wrapped your head around it all, you might feel a bit excluded from the game, fumbling around not doing much. But, stick with it. Once it clicks, you'll see that it's a game of surprising depth."
