76561198013132245,Recommended,271240,35216375,Posted: 25 September,all,huminado,"I wish I could have played this great game earlier... but of course, Stardock insists on not giving demos, and they always overprice their games, along with milking customers for years and years before any semblance of a finished product is available.  And I'm not even sure they'll ever finish any of their current games.  They just may keep adding on to them for perpetuity.  But for whatever reason, when this game became available for 50% off, I decided it was worth a try.I only have started to play, but I'm not disappointed so far.  Having played Sid Meier's Railroads, this game has similar elements, but is more cut-throat.  People have complained about the overabundance of options - and that is true, but it just shows that this is a gamer's game, with geeks blathering on and on incessantly about the nuances of so many strategic elements.  It's fine with me!  I would rather a game was never fully comprehensible, than that it was too simple.There is a huge amount of guesswork in this game in that you try to predict which resources will become scarce and which ones will be overproduced, and building up for harvesting the former while just buying out the latter when needed.The games seem to play relatively quickly - maybe under 3 hours or so.Is the game worth the full price?  Only if you are a die-hard economic sim fan, or money is no object.  I feel satisfied paying 50% off - I got something close to a ""finished-level"" game, and the price was about average.  I bought the ""Gold"" bundle that came with the Jupiter and other DLCs.  I'm not sure I'll ever find time to play all the expansions, but they are nice to have available.The learning curve is much higher than the simple appearance implies.  There are some very complex interelationships to build up, and timing vulnerabilities those relationships hinge on.  You can't see what stockpiles your opponents might have up their sleeve, waiting for the opportune moment to buy you out.The game is written in the Unity3D engine, which means the graphics tend to lag a little.  Some people have complained about this, but for an economic sim, I could not care less if I lose some frames now and then.  This is not a shooter - it's more like a clicker.  Frame rate doesn't affect gameplay hardly at all, and I haven't noticed any issues yet with a minimal level laptop, so I think it's a nonissue.  Still if you're very picky you might want to consider that.In-game voice acting is good.  Prose tone is semi-humorous (some references to slave-driving in the real world that hits a bit too close to home to be ""haha"" funny).  The core humor of Offworld is watching helplessly as your company slowly melts down!  The artwork is light-hearted, cartoony and trace amounts of psycho: B+ - for an eco-sim the artwork adds good flavor.  The marketting video voice acting doesn't match the lightness of the cartoony artwork - it's a bit nonsequetor.I have not found ANY part of this game (in the current state) that feels like they are still holding some major component back for a future DLC.  Of all the turn-offs of Stardock, that has been my biggest gripe, and it's a welcome change not to feel like I paid for a feature-lacking-but-already-planned-for-future-customer-milking-DLC version of the game.  However, if I'd bought it when it first came out - that would certainly have been the case, so I think I timed it okay.  The only risk I can think of here is if they create some new version that becomes a defacto standard, the mod community will split up.The modding for this game looks delicious!  I'm not sure though whether a full re-skin is possible.This looks like it could be a lot of fun to play multiplayer, especially at a LAN party with several friends."
