,Not Recommended,271240,31371849,Posted: 26 April,all,Kensei,"It's clear to me that just like in the game, the developer's goal is to rake in the profits.Game is not worth it's asking price, especially when things like difficulty is a DLC. Even the map editor is a DLC. But let's forget about that for a second, after all, the quality of a game isn't defined by it's studio's greedy practices.So is OTC a good game? Well, it's average. You play as a CEO of a company, and your job is to setup a production pipeline on Mars. Along the way you'll have to compete with rival companies, and should you win, you basically monopolize Mars. Sounds pretty cool on paper, but in reality it's underwhelming.Some people might say there's a deep tactical aspect, but that is a lie. The company mechanics will dictate your playstyle, and it won't be long untill you figure out that there is only ONE playstyle, and that's the intended one. Robots pump out power, Scavangers can build with ductape and gum, Expansive can, well, expand faster, and Science are nerds that think they can do things better by skipping resource mining, when in reality they are gimped.The way this works is that every ""race"" has their strengths in different stages of the game, scavengers take the early, bots take the mid, expansive take late, and science take endgame. Obviously depending on the map and resource availability, this changes depending on the player. Unfortunately that's as far as the depth of this game can take you.At the end of the day, every game plays, and ends, the same way. Even after buying some DLC's (things that should be features of the base game) that added some variety to the game, it was hardly engaging. A lack of units hurts the gameplay, at times forcing you to sit and wait, even if you max out the play speed. The endgame is another thing that never changes, eventually the local market gets saturated by all the companies producing pretty much everything, requiring you to build some rockets and export your stuff offworld.Whoever buys the most shares at a colony/oposing company, be it by building modules, fullfilling wholesale orders, or by burying your competition in debt, wins the game. Along the way you can utilize some special ""skills"" which will cost you depending on how often it's used. The price of these skills is shared between players, so if everybody decides to nuke each other's resources pools, the price will skyrocket pretty fast. This is probably the first game that made a NUKE, boring. Like everything, these skills are mostly underwhelming, so don't expect to be blasting things to bits, or building an army. Your one and only weapon is the market, and while certainly a capable and formidable weapon, it's not enough to hold this game against other, more fairly priced and more feature packed products.So ultimately, is the game FUN? That's after all, what counts. Assuming you don't buy any DLC's, you'll have it all figured out in about 4-5 hours of gameplay. It'll take you about 6-7 with the DLCs. After that, it's rinse and repeat. The rest depends on how much endurance you have for the same thing over and over again.I really gave this game a chance, went as far as looking up some of the more intricate mechanics, trying out all the races, in all 3 campaign modes. Unfortunately, as unique this game is, it's also as uniquely boring, at least for me. If you get suckered into buying it based on the thousands of positive reviews, you'll only have yourself to blame when you get disappointed.People are having difficulty distinguishing between unique that is new, and unique that is entertaining."
,Recommended,271240,23553501,"Posted: 14 June, 2016",all,The Faceless Man,Absolutely amazing game. It gets very intense especially when you see the opposition's stock price rising. If you do not set yourself on a good foundation early in the game you will regret it later on. Amazing game I am addicted to it.
,Not Recommended,271240,26086777,"Posted: 17 October, 2016",all,Kim Jong-un,"I really thought I was going to love this game, and I did, during the first couple of tutorial missions. I thought to myself ""wow, this is amazing! I can't wait to colonize Mars! I'm going to spend hours and hours spreading across the planet!""Sadly, after the first couple of tutorials they start introducing mechanics that make the game less fun. Once you really get into the game, you're no longer focused on colonizing, because you get an extremely limited amount of buildings. Once they're built, you need to watch a little stock ticker and sell off your spare resources. You can't do it all at once though, because selling dips the price, so you need to pause the game every 30 seconds or so to do it. It gets really tedious.There's a goofy stock mechanic where you dump all of your extra money into your own stock (which doesn't seem to do much because people can and will still buy you out) and other people's stock, where you buy them out. If you get bought out (which can happen with no warning if you're not paying attention) it's instant game over.This is a well made game and I'm sure lots of people will find it's what they're interested in playing, but a 30 minute game of micromanaging silicon prices isn't what I want to play. Maybe that's my fault for not looking into what this was more thoroughly, but I can't think of anyone I would recommend this to.Weak thumbs down. Sorry game."
