76561198021244149,Recommended,271240,23984027,"Posted: 1 July, 2016",all,Pangalactic,"What an absolutely fantastic game!The premise is very simple: you are on Mars, you have a company, and you can mine/produce various resources as well as buy and sell them. Your goal is to buy all  of your competitiors (like a real world market aquisiton, you need 51% of their shares to control them).And here is what makes this game so brilliant:1) You have complete freedom over what you do - there are no compulsory buildings or anything of that sort, you can choose any strategy and even change it on the fly (glass is becoming too cheap? Then destroy all your glass production faciliteis and build electronics factories instead), so there is never a set path and you are always engaged2) The free market that makes the game superdynamic. Let's say you've decided to produce chemicals and sell them on the market. But if everyone starts producing chemicals, then obviously there will be a surplus of them, the prices will go down and no one will be making any money! This makes you constantly think about what do you want to produce, what the competition are producing, what will be required in 5 minutes (if everyone will be upgrading and will need glass for it, but no one is producing it, then maybe you can do it right now - or simply buy it cheap now and sell at a much higher price later), and seek the most profitable endeavor on the market.3) The factions - there are four of them, and they all play very differently. For example, the Scavengers use no steel, but carbon instead for their buildings. So, if there is just a little bit of carbon on the map, then you can easily organize a carbon monopoly! Or, let's say you believe steel is going to be very expensive in the game - than you can take the Scavengers, and avoid the much higher costs of building that everyone else will have.All of them have their disctinct advantages and disadvantages, and you get to choose any of the four every game!4) The abilities - you can buy them of the black market, and oh boy can they mess up the production!The energy prices are high? EMP your opponent's solar panels, and he will have an insane debt from having to buy all the expenisve electricityThe Scavengers are doing very well? Underground nuke their carbon deposits, so that their productions falls almost two to three times and slow themm downThere are tons of abilities, and you can buy them as well as protection from them, and using them at the right moment can win you or lose the game5)And, of course, the tension - it lasts till the absolute end and always keeps you on the toes, and makes each game very fun and engaging.There are tons of other nuances and depth to the game, but you can find out most of it during your games, as this review would be way too long for it :)Overall, it a an extremely dynamic and fun strategy game, and I would definitely recommend it to anyone!"
76561197966775517,Recommended,271240,16688727,"Posted: 24 June, 2015",all,Gustov,"Picked this game up during the summer sale and I have to say I'm very glad that I did.  This game is TOTALLY playable despite still being in Early Access.  The developers have created a great inter dependency of resources and how they're used and what they're used for and by whom that allows for a deep level of strategizing and planning ahead of time while hoping that someone else's plans don't come to fruition before yours.  This is not a game that's ruined by ""I made more tanks than you GG"" by any stretch.  I HIGHLY recommend this game in its current state!"
,Recommended,271240,22727072,"Posted: 30 April, 2016",all,Patrick,"It looks like an RTS but plays closer to a real-time version of a board game, specifically, a worker placement game. Whereas worker placement games tend to fall under the Eurogame umbrella (i.e. boring abstract pieces of uninteractive garbage) Offworld Trading Company thankfully doesn't fall into that trap.You're on Mars to make mad dosh and prevent your fellow corporations from doing the same. The black market exists for you to fry their steel industry at key points with EMPs, to hire pirates to prey upon their shipping lines, and to cause energy blackouts.Every decision has heavy weight, especially the decision to spend claims, which is the game's territory system. You can't endlessly expand your borders like Civilization. Every time you upgrade your HQ you gain 4-5 tiles' worth of claims which you can then spend to create facilities on land. The level of long-term strategy is high here because you can't refund those claims; the most you can do is destroy the building, which may not even help you if you need a building with a different resource.I would recommend this to any strategy gamer who has grown bored of traditional manifestations of the genre. Don't forget to make lodse money!https://youtu.be/ON-7v4qnHP8"
,Recommended,271240,23595921,"Posted: 16 June, 2016",all,MasterBlaster,"If the idea of an almost purely economical RTS ""battle"" appeals to you, then this is a game you definitely should own. However I feel like the 40 dollar price tag is too steep for what it is.First off, where this game really shines is multiplayer. Small battles, even just 1v1 with a friend, are really fun. Everything is about speed. The game is different from most traditional city builders. There's not a whole lot of ""city building"" going on. That is to say, the way that you decide to lay out your ""town"" is not overly important to the game. You can get certain bonuses for having some buildings next to others. For instance, placing any building next to another of the same type gives you a production bonus that is stackable, and buildings touching your HQ don't need fuel for transporting goods. Other than that, city design isn't a prominent aspect. Instead, the gameplay is all about speed. Claim territory, make money, and claim more territory as fast as possible.More often than not, the person who manages to claim the best territory the fastest will end up winning. Because of this, games can often be decided in the first 5-10 minutes. They also usually don't last more than 20-30 minutes. That is part of what makes the game so cool. If you're looking for a quick multiplayer session with a friend, it can become a natural choice if you're both good at it. Skirmishes are very fast paced and don't last long so you can squeeze games in whenever you feel like it. However it's also one of the game's hindrances.I think it could do with a good deal more content. Games almost feeltoofast. You rush to figure out what the key resources on the map are and acquire them, rush to build some factories, rush to research some technology to give you advantages, always keeping an eye on the fluctuating prices of various commodities and having to deal with your opponents sabotaging your production through various ""black market"" means. There's so much to keep track of that games can flip around on you in an instant. One second you can be on top, well ahead of the game, next thing you know WHAM game over you just got bought. It can often leave you going ""what the hell just happened?""This is part of what makes it so fun and deadly, but at times it can feel somewhat lacking. So much of the game is just looking at numbers on the sidebar, constantly guaging prices, resources, buying, and selling. The actual graphics are very nice, but the funny thing is you don't actually spend a lot of time looking at the graphics, because winning is all about crunching numbers quickly. In my opinion the game would be better if there were some more layers of strategy that involved the actual graphical, planet of mars, city building related stuff. That would make this game a 9/10 for me at least. Alas, it does not, but if the devs keep developing it as they are it will get better.If you get it on sale, it's definitely worth it."
