,Recommended,271240,29945837,Posted: 15 February,all,krazyhades,"OTC is a brilliant game that has carved out its own sub-genre, ""economic RTS"". I've played mostly multiplayer myself, and WOW the games feel intense, without needing armies and war to make it so. The first time you spend a a chunk of change to place some glass kilns, only to have an opponent crash the price of glass by selling away a huge stockpile they've been sitting on...you will know fury and despair! And when you figure out their entire economy hinges on a particular carbon tile, which you then permanently undermine with an underground nuke, an evil corporate joy will fill your heart as you watch them sink into debt.This is not a game about microing your zerglings with 400 APM. It's about making choices and predicting how the market value of resources will change. And yet it still manages to get your heart thumping away. ""Can I upgrade quickly enough to steal that beautiful tile right next to my opponent's base? Can I survive the Mars night paying through the nose for electricity because my only source is solar panels? Can I win this stock-buying race, or is my company going to be taken away from me with the NOTICE OF TERMINATION screen?This game is seriously mindblowing in its elegant design, but it's not just some cerebral experience. It's tense, it's cutthroat, and it's absolutely superb."
