76561198030431916,Recommended,271240,29011995,Posted: 4 January,all,IndieInc.,"I love Offworld Trading Company (OTC), it's the deep and modern non-military, economic strategy game we have all been waiting for!Back in high school we had these business simulation games where you would take charge of a company producing good X, in competition with similar companies.You'd decide how to spend the funds available to you - how much you'd produce, advertise, research and invest in more production capacity.Each round of the game would represent 3 months of doing business and you would make one decision per round.After everyone submitted their decisions, the round would end, the simulation would calculate everyone's performance and luck, and quarterly reports would come in.It was a peculiar sort of high to see that my company had done well and beaten others to market share and/or profits.If you can relate to this, you will like OTC.In OTC you take charge of one of four types of companies on Mars in competition with one to seven (depending on what kind of matchup you prefer) other companies.In a single match that lasts roughly 30 minutes you decide on the location of you HQ (to where all your resources are shipped), which land hexes you claim and what you mine or produce to make more money than your competitors.The company to seize control of all others (via buying more than 50% of their shares) wins.While the overall goal of each game is clear and simple, the game's mechanics are many and varied, providing ever-shifting sub-goals, making each match a unique experience.As of version 1.0 release, players have to consider:Starting market prices,Nearby colony requirements,Land and Resources available on map,The Black Market,Personal play preferences,The competition :)Considering these elements defines the initial minutes of a match.As time progresses, companies upgrade their HQs to gain access to more land claims as well as bonuses like patents, Black Market goodies or extra claims.Eventually companies consume and can produce so much as to completely dominate the market and influence profits and business strategies of others.Sometimes denying profits for a competitor is better than making a profit for yourself.As of JAN-2017, OTC has these features that keep me coming back:Competitive and friendly community - Offworld Trading Company channel on Discord always has some of the top players around.Daily Challenge - a hand-crafted, unique scenario that requires you to discern the winning strategy against AI players in various settings.Ceres expansion that replaces the Mars planetary setting with the Ceres asteroid - different resources, patents and market dynamics.Ranked Multiplayer - play against others in a hacker-free setting. 1x1 or 4-player free-for-all matches available.New players may find the learning curve steep, but doing the thorough tutorial and giving the wiki a read should provide enough of gameplay basics to jump right in.The only real complaint I have is the cost. I can not say the game is worth the hefty price of $40, but wait for a sale and do pick it up.8/10"
,Recommended,271240,26037762,"Posted: 14 October, 2016",all,Codelizard,"It's fun with literally any number of players except 3.It's in the same vein as other economic hostile-takeover games like TTD but it's much faster-paced, so instead of a game taking days to complete, it's over in 20-30 minutes. This is a good thing. The time between ""It's obvious who the winner is"" and ""The winner is declared"" is very short. Games don't last very long after the first buyout, so if you're playing multiple rounds with friends, you won't have to sit out long.The basic premise is to acquire resources and sell them to get money to repeat the process. Resource prices change accordingly every time something is bought or sold, and there are various market manipulations that can be done. There's plenty of ways to mess with your opponent there, and you can buy usable-once-only sabotages for further shenanigans.It has its problems - the first buyout practically doubles your stock price, so in a 3-player game the first buyout determines the winner; the remaining player has a 0% chance of catching up and should just concede immediately. The Offworld Market is a necessary evil on Mars (as otherwise all resource prices drop to 1, but whoever has them is basically guaranteed to win) and utterly useless on Ceres (as all resource prices eventually become 1000). The AI is WAY too good at the game, as it makes no attempts to hide that it can and will react instantly to situations, inputting commands faster than any human possibly could.Overall though, it's an excellent strategy game that doesn't take nearly as long to play a round of compared to others in the genre. A good game to grab if you like economic games or quick strategies."
