76561198309990321,Recommended,271240,28283224,"Posted: 9 December, 2016",all,jalves,"So far I am enjoying the game.  If you are of the analytical mindset like me and into economics/the markets, you will enjoy it alot.  I also have always really enjoyed strategy games.  That said I would imagine such people is only a small subset of most gamers so I wonder how the player count will hold up over time.I like how the typical match does not feel too short or long.  Maybe a half hour or so.  There is not too many APM but at the same time there is plenty to think about and manage.My biggest issue with this game is that the graphics to performance ratio is in my view lacking.  Meaning, even with an overclocked Geforce 1070 and 6600 process and 16 gb DDR4 ram I am seeing my frame per second dip sometimes below 30.  Now granted for an overhead strategy game based more on numbers and thinking this is not as critical as say a first person shooter or racing game.  Nonetheless, the optimization should be better, especially considering the graphics are nothing to write home about.  Honestly the graphics are no better then starcraft 2 which is how old now?  Considering this game came out in 2016, they should of optimized it better, I get better frames per second on witcher 3 at ultra!To further expand on the graphics, for example all deposits whether it be water or silicon have the same exact symbol!  The only difference is the color.  Couldn't the developers of thought of something a bit more creative to represent the deposits?  The ""landscape"" is so bland you barely recognize it outside vaugely referencing it to what may produce better power or where you can't build.To sum it up.  I think the actual gameplay mechanics are pretty well thought out and pretty fun to play.  But i think the graphic innovation and optimization seems to have gotten the lazy end of the stick especially for the price this goes for (though I got it on a steam sale for half off).I would give it a 8.5 out of 10 but that is only because I am into stock markets and economics personally, for most people it probably would be around a 6.5."
