76561197961578109,Recommended,271240,22731749,"Posted: 30 April, 2016",all,Lameness,"Offworld Trading Company is an economic warfare based real time strategy game. That makes it quite an interesting take on the RTS genre.How does the 'warfare' work? Well, you and your competitors mine raw materials and produce goods - and sell it on the shared market. And if someone else has a building you don't want them to have, it may accidentally explode.. or you 'borrow' it for some time to win the race to one of the juicy patents (buffs only one player can have). In the end, you want to make money more quickly than the other people (and avoid debt!), in order to buyout their companies. And .. sometimes you may have to manipulate the market prices a tiny bit..So how does the strategy layer of OTC look it? Well, one important aspect is that space is limited. Every time you upgrade your HQ, you can claim some more (4-5) tiles on the map. These normally are tiles either next to your HQ or tiles with resources on it.Since (good) resources tiles are limited, you can create the situation where you nearly have a monopoly on a raw resource. And if everyone has to buy from you (via the market), you can make quite a profit by actively generating this situation. Doing so is tricky though, since at the start of the match, the map is covered with fog of war - and only when your HQ position is selected, the whole map is revealed. Might turn out that whole map is covered with silicon.. but there barely is any carbon! Time to change long term plans!Once you own a tile, its yours for the rest of the match. This is where good positioning and foresight comes into play, because whatever buildings you are going to use, those have to be on these limited tiles. Got those now-useless mines on the other end of the map? Well, just put factories there instead. However, transporting goods costs fuel, which requires water to make, which drives up prices and reduces profit.All producing buildings get adjacency bonuses (each +50% for 2 buildings, +75% for 3). So your first idea might be ""well, get some mines in the middle of nowhere and a big cluster of tiles at my HQ to maximize adjacency"". However, this leaves your production very vulnerable to area of effect sabotage by that dude that doesn't like you. Ouch.The market prices rise and drop depending on what all players do. This requires you to switch up production on the fly. You produced food? Well, turns out over the last minutes prices for the required water skyrocketed, so you don't make a profit anymore. Better replace those farms with something better.A classic example is that no one cares to produce energy in the early game (not profitable; not helping to upgrade HQ). This causes the energy prices to rise in the midgame, which you can actively abuse by then dumping energy on the market (while sabotaging everyone else who tries that).The game has four factions, each with a spin on how they work. -Expansionists get more claims and cheaper buildings, allowing them to be more flexible-Robots don't need life support supplies - and get adjacency not only for same type of buildings, but also if a supplier is next to a factory.-By the power of science, factories can use the resource tiles below them!-Real Scavengers don't use steel like everyone else, but use carbon - which allows them to pull off above play with energy production very effectively. Also they love sabotaging.So would I recommend the game? Like I said, I think it's a very interesting take on the RTS genre. It has a lovely soundtrack (Christopher Tin, aka Baba Yetu/Civ 4 Main Theme). I'm personally not sure about the 40 Eur price tag though.. ouch.. When it's on sale for 20, I would say pick it up. Since I can't comment on the multiplayer and its longevity and dynamic yet, I'm not sure whether I personally would give 30 for it. Then again, I'm a very conservative buyer.I honestly fear that the maximum strategic depth may be much shallower than say Starcraft (1!) or the Wargame series - but I think that can be expected, since market mechanics and its potential generally probably aren't fully explored yet. SC and WG are in their 4th+ iteration, in the more classic multiplayer RTS style and thus strategically much more refined. I'm very curious how they'll expand on this mechanic, though."
76561197963922877,Recommended,271240,16800650,"Posted: 29 June, 2015",all,Kayos,"I've been a RTS fan since the first warcraft game. Generally I favor the more military focused games like warcraft, starcraft, red alert, age of empires; so I was a little wary of giving this game a try. So glad I did.I really enjoy the pacing of this game. Yes, it can move quickly, but for the most part it doesn't require the twitch reflexes that starcraft 2 and other modern RTS games demand. For those who say this game is too shallow, I couldn't disagree any more. Yes, it's true there are less building options and tech trees to work with, but Offworld has more than enough to keep the game engaging. When dealing  with an ever-changing economy you don't need tiers of tech to have content that is hard to master.Mastery in this game is learning to predict your opponents' market schemes, adapting to the chaning economy, and knowing when to take risks in certain investments such as a new patent, claim or black market. While predicting, adapting and risk taking aren't new skills to the RTS genre, having to master them in a passive setting rather than an active go-attack-em setting makes for some new challenges that I've really enjoyed trying to learn.More Thoughts:It is true the tutorial could be a little more thorough, but after a couple of hours, you should be able to figure out the gist.This is just me, but I think the Black Market takes the fun out of the game. I'm sure with more experience I could make better use of the black market, but for now the cost/benefit ratio doesn't seem to justify any purchase except for the new claims.  My biggest beef with the black market is that it takes away from the game's best feature, a rts focused primarily on economy. With the black market enabled it can get really annoying when your production is stopped, especially because it doesn't really hurt you, it just slows the game down. Thankfully there is an option to disable the black market, which i've found myself doing on every game now.8/10"
