,Recommended,271240,14445289,"Posted: 13 February, 2015",all,Canechurch,"OTC is an interesting concept. Right now I do find it enjoyable and I look forward to the addition of leagues and ladders.Gameplay is already quite polished and it looks nice. It's an interesting take on the RTS genre and I would love to see more games like this.If I could select one change off the bat, it would be more market information and more dynamic markets. Right now the only truly dynamic resources is energy. Global prices are, it seems, driven by either player stockpile purchases or running deficits, which someone else could capitalize on. I'd like to see the markets function by net contribution and less stockpile driven, so rather than attempting to accumulate valuable goods and selling them off in bulk to buyout opponents have running market contribution. There seems to be a bit too much ""random invisible supply and demand we dont know"" driving market function. Giving us some idea of ambient demand and supply balance or even ""global stockpile"" that determines pricing would be nice, and then introducing exogenous price shocks to randomly shift market prices would be cool too. Something to give the pricing a bit more depth.Similarly, the share ownership function could also gain more depth, giving extra utility to ownership would be quite interesting. Defensive ownership blocks provide no real benefit if you're behind, and spending that cash on buying yourself only means you can't spend it on further expansion which I could see leading to increasingly snowbally gameplay. It seems like it would always be better to build ownership blocks in other companies.Finally adding more depth to the debt system would be quite cool. Right now debt seems like it works primarily as a death spiral - if you don't get your basic resources up and running you just enter a fixed debt growth and unless market prices (which we dont know enough about) swing your way you won't be able to get yourself out of it. Allowing players to manually take on debt in order to boost their economy would be a nice idea.None-the-less its an interesting and enjoyable game on to play on early access release which is a rare find, and with additional work it could become a genuinely deep and interesting competitive game."
