76561197962460010,Recommended,271240,14505657,"Posted: 16 February, 2015",all,[Qc] Gnome,"So, you came here most likely wondering: ""Should i buy this early access game? Is worth it?"" Well, the short answer to this is: ""YES"". I'll review some of the game features here and, if you're in a hurry, there is a tl;dr section at the end.What's the game?You're in charge of a trading colony on Mars and you compete with other companies to gain monopoly on the planet. It fits really nice with all the talks going on about an actual manned expedition to Mars.How to win?You have to buy stocks of the other players and gain control of their company. You win the game when you have bought all the other companies. If your own company gets bought, you instantly loose the game.What's the gameplay?You start off with a little cash and ressources (or none, there are options to set it before starting a game). You'll then have to build some buildings (like a mine or a steel mill) to harvest some ressources, be it iron or steel, etc. You can then transform these ressources into building materials or goods which you use or sell on a global market. All the players affect that market; if someone sells a lot of a product, its price is going to go down and, on the contrary, if someone buys a lot of a ressource, its price is going up for everybody.With the money and the ressources, you can expand your colony, buy some stocks or use the black market (i'll get back to it later). In order to build more, you'll need to spend some claims. Claims that allow you, and only you, to use a tile in the game. So, especially at the beggining of a game, the fastest to find and lay claims on ressources is most likely to have the better spots. Those claims are obtained by expending your HQ or bought on the black market. So, the twist of the game is, you'll be struggling with few claims and you'll have to prioritise what building you need. Are you going to try and be self-sufficient? Or maybe invest in a pricey ressource gathering infrastructure? That's the kind of questions you'll be dealing with most of the game.You HQ and your ressource transforming building will need some base ressources that you can mine yourself, or buy on the market (thus making it pricier). When you're lacking a ressource it increases your debt, which affect the value of your stocks. If your stocks are cheap, it's easier for other players to buy and you might loose the game. So watch that debt carefully.Is that it? A ressource harvesting/transforming game?Mostly, yes. There are some researches and upgrading you can do in the game, but you'll spend those hard-earned claims mostly on harvest/producing more.What's the blackmarket?You can't directly attack other players, at least in a classic RTS way. There are no soldiers and you can't steal a nice spot claimed, but you can affect their production with the help of some saboteurs available on the blackmarket. For some money, you can dynamite one of their building or launch an EMP that will freeze their buildings for sometime. Of course, you can also be the target of such attacks and, if you're not defended (with goons also from the blackmarket), you won't know who hit you.Of course, as it is the goal of the game, you can buy other players stocks and then win the game.Is it a good early access?Yes. I haven't add issues with the game crashing. It's working really well on my end and all the features are there. Of course, some elements are still to be updated. As an exemple, there are no dedicated servers provided for multiplayer games, making the game quit if the host leaves the game. Like in the good old days.But, for the rest, everything is there and you'll be able to enjoy all the mechanics.Any other notable feautres?A few. This game has a lot replayability, every map is random generated so no game is going to be like the previous one. A complete game lasts around 30-45 minutes, providing that you're the winner. A few options available before starting the game like a tighter debt or masquerade can add a little something to a game.There must be some downsides, no?Sure, but I would insist that they do not compromise the quality of the game mechanics. Except for the dedicated servers I spoke about earlier, the voiceover is actually horrible. You can't understand half and there is no clear logic in them (like, one faction gets a robotic male voice, then there is a female voice that speaks for them, no apparent reason why). Also, th UI might get a little more responsive, the buttons especially. Events are shown in a small text log on the right, but they should appear bigger since they can greatly affect your game (a shortage or surplus on a ressource can be a random event that will influence the price of said ressources, for exemple).And the price, for about 500mo of game, not that nice graphics and all, is a bit high. But, in my opinion, it is worth it.TL;DRPros:Great gameplay mechanicsActual subjectExcellent replayabilityFun multiplayerIndirect attacks with blackmarketOut of the box strategy gameCons:VoiceoverNo dedicated serversPriceIn the end: really great game that will get you an alternative RTS we don't see much these days. If you like strategy games, wargames and ressource management games: this is for you. I recommend it without any doubt.9,5/10"
