76561198006358574,Not Recommended,271240,31696260,Posted: 11 May,all,Name Lips,"I really, really wanted to like this game. But I finally had to admit that it wasn't for me.The game is surprisingly fast-paced for a economic, supply-and-demand game. Matches can be 15 minutes or less. This isn't necessarily a problem, but I had a very hard time understanding how to develop a strategy. At any given moment there are a thousand different things that you can do, and dozens of goals I could be using those things to be working towards. But I had a very hard time seeing how the pieces fit together into a sensible whole.I wanted desperately to slow things down, so I could examine my opponents, figure out what they were doing, figure out how to counter it... but there's no time for that. I spend most of the game frantically building stuff and not knowing why, or if it will help me. When I win, I don't feel like I won because of skill or strategy. And when I lose, I have no idea why.Playing OTC gives me a constant feeling of not being QUITE smart enough. I keep feeling like there's a lot of depth to this game, but I can't figure out how to dig into it.I want to say the game is ""complex"" but that's not quite it. It's more... obscured. I'm sure it would all make sense if I could see it clearly enough, if I just had time to turn it over and take it apart and figure out how it worked. Since I don't know how to develop a strategy for myself, I get no information when I examine an opponent's base. I know I'm SUPPOSED to be reacting to what they're doing, building and buying and selling in a way that counters their strategy so I can defeat them, but I can't figure out how to do that. Since everything I'm doing feels random, everything the opponents do seems random too."
