76561198159611533,Recommended,271240,18544977,"Posted: 18 October, 2015",all,Study Danger,"If you believe appearance doesn't make a difference, then it doesn't.  But if you do, it does.  I really, really wanted to like this game for its appearance.I think OTC has most of the strenghs of the Civ series with more replayability, due in large part to real-time pacing.  Beginners fear not!  The single-player version defaults with a pause button and save-or-bail options!  Advanced players fear much!  Multi-player doesn't!  But I digress.  Real time pacing enhances replayability by deemphasizing the start and playing a perfect strategy, and emphasizing making the fewest mistakes.  And who doesn't want to make fewer mistakes the next time.I wanted to like OTC.  I liked it.  Still do.  Got some hours under my belt and still nowhere near ready for prime time.  Still single-player, pausing and saving, and trying something new.  I really, really like this game.//  A Robot Colony  //////////////////Figuring out the Robotic Colony first really worked for me.  Given lots of resources and Employee difficulty, map options, I was able to get experience with interface, the upgrade options and sequence, and the financial system, and win consistently against the AI.  Always a good thing.  The financial system is the key to winning the game.  The AI is pretty good at finding local optima, better than I am anyway.  I'm better at global optima and was glad of the head start Employee difficulty gave.  And lots of resources ment the build script for my Robotic Colony was relatively simple so I could concentrate on the financial system.  And finding a nice big fat organic colony to buy out, er, ally with.  (Look, I know we don't have a lot in common, but . . .  What, that gyser of molten high-test steel behind me?  We meteored into a huge pile of iron ore.  By design.  3% over expectations, actually.  So, I can crank out launchers like Detroit does cars and you can crank out organic export products like a Kansas farmer.  As long as you aren't against me, we _will_ win.  :)"
