,Recommended,271240,16500760,"Posted: 18 June, 2015",all,HighLordBlunticulus,"1-Hour, First Impressions, Early Access, ReviewA good, fast-pased but relativley relaxing economy game.In it's current state, this game litterally throws you into the deep(ish) end. Non-intuitive game mechanics and lack of any true and thorough tutorial makes searching up a guide on build orders and tips almost essential. To give you an idea of the situation; I failed the first tutorial twice because it's not clear, nor does it explain that you have a ""claim"" limit. (more on this later)Once the surface is scratched, and mechanics are better understood, the game becomes much better. Many things in the game will appeal to fans of mass, streaming-economy RTSs. Real-time indirect agression against the enemy player is very remeniscent of other games such a Sid Mier's ""Trains"".The game can be very punishing towards mistakes made, a single wrong move in the early-mid game can spell disaster for your company. One such example is the ""claims"" mechanic, which gives you a limit on the number of tiles you can take before progressing. Take the wrong tile, and even if you remove the building there, you cannot unclaim it, leaving you with an incorrect, useless tile for the rest of the game.Despite it's unforgiving nature, Offworld Trading Company is already (despite being early access) an excellent game with great potential for hours of fun."
