76561197976706478,Recommended,271240,20284822,"Posted: 4 January, 2016",all,{BCA} Xenophanes,"A solid game that breaks away from the normal RTS collect 1-2 resources and then send your army over to the enemy to kill their workers because that hurts them the most.In this game you're tasked with laying out a plan to develop your resources in a solid production line. Against the AI you don't have to deal with many hiccups, but unlike what the negative reviews have said about 0 depth, when you get in to multiplayer skirmishes you've now got to build efficiently, and take in to account what they might do to you.For instance, there are 4 factions, each different than the other, if you can keep in mind the resources that each needs, you can punish your opponents my stealing them, or stealing their building, but this may leave you open to similar attacks. Then further from that you have to manage your debt, you might have a short term victory, but if they cripple you at the right time, they can send you spiraling in to debt which will stop you from further attacks or defense tactics.So, to those who wrote ""0 depth"", try winning some multiplayer matches.The pros:- One of the most intelligent queueing systems I've seen, you can practice against the AI while waiting for a 1v1 skirmish, and it saves your game, so next time you're in queue, you can pick up against the AI where you left off.!!- Varied gameplay because resources change and other players playstyles and decisions change per match.- A unique (afaik) game style that focuses more on the resource management side of RTS rather than militaristic side.The cons:- Fewer than I'd like number of players online at any given time, this can make finding matches a headache, and yes playing against the AI becomes less and less satisfying.- If you want to play a match unveiled like a normal multiplayer 1v1 against the AI, you have to start it outside the queueing system, but  from the tooltip it looks like this will change, so it could be an Early Access temporary con.- No queues other than 1v1, (Missing 2v2, 3v3, 4v4, or FFA queues)Compared to many early access games this game is quite polished, I feel like this is how early access SHOULD work, you've got the solid core game, but the blemishes are showing.Neutral things I attribute to early access:-- Lack of player base (Steam Early Access has burned a lot of people)- Voices are mostly Google reader sounding things, except the director who says ""Uhhh, your stock is being sold"" :)- Other mapsTL:DRIt's a solid game, great gameplay, replayability if you're in to multiplayer. It's early access, and behaves like one. Implemented the gameplay first, now it puts on the polish."
,Recommended,271240,20464076,"Posted: 10 January, 2016",all,Ψ | Psi-Lapse,"A virtual economy where you create things; sell things; and buy out your competitors. So heres the crazy thing: Its shockingly complexFirst; the AI.the AI knows what its doing but it doesn't seem to want to over-saturate the economy as I'm so keen on doing.Dunno if that was intentional but if you can make a product not at all worth the actual product; it makes it harder for them to earn the money needed to buy your stocks.Second; the black marketIt would be hilarious to blow up someone's mine on a skype call; but otherwise you can basically shake it off. They never really get you to a choking point. Pirates kept stealing really pathetic amounts of water from me, for example (about 30-50 water a minute or so) and it didn't even matter because my production supported beyond that. The worst ones are the magnet storm and emp. The rest (save for nukes which I always buy just to get it out of the game if its being auctioned) doesn't even matter. If you are producing and you're staying afloat; go ahead and laugh. Otherwise its a minor inconvenince.Third; the economy itselfIt's a simple Supply/Demand type thing and is constantly checking itself and I love that. Things feel as if they have value despite being totally meaningless just like in real life.Forth; gameplayThe game is smoothish on my laptop and is graphically pleasing. Its in early access but that's not going to excuse anything. A mine looks a mine and a transport looks like a transport. Each faction looks very different from each other.Fifth; the 'realisim'Each faction has its own voice; but is as well quite robotic. Think Hal 9000 but just slightly less human sounding. Its a bit hard to put into words. the Robotic faction sounds like a male GPS voice, the scavenger faction sounds like a british robot, expansive sounds like a female GPS voice, and so on. Each mine reproduces whatever item its tile says and each tiles material stacks (0-3 but 0 is just a blank tile) and the amount of stuff that exists keeps it interestingMy biggest issue is the games one limiting factor; claim titles. all tiles on the game are fair game but you can only grab x amount of until you level up your hq (up to level 5 and that comes quickly; trust me) And, if you place something down by mistkae; and so you go to destroy whatever you placed on it; well you just wasted material. That tile is yours son. Congrats. Didn't need that carbon? Too bad.  The only way to get rid of a tile is to auction it and the game never actually tells you how to auction things. It just introduces it maybe 10 mins into one of the tutorial missions. Never tells you how; just lets you particpate.My other issue is how the game handles debt. You got two big numbers; the current money you have, and a possible accurued debt. The idea, of course, is to not need to buy things, and if you need to, rather than subtracting it from your current cash; it just created debt that you can pay off whenever you feel like. While that's nice it doesn't feel like a negative. Its not pressing.The game doesn't remind you of the hole you're digging for yourself; it just points it out with a red number and that's it. Each new day it'll go up by x percentage but what does it matter? The only real negative is you don't make any profits (all profits made through like, selling power is funneled to your debt rather than your cash pool) but you can still make money by selling materials; and you can then pay the debt back 1k per click.But why when I don't feel the need to because nothing bad happens.I don't feel punished by the growing red number and I feel that might be an issue.7/10"
,Recommended,271240,21069302,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,Jet,"Great game! I managed to get 3 hrs of gameplay out of just the tutorials, without doing any multiplayer or campaign mode. So that to me is a great start. The graphics are pretty and the interface is really easy to use. For an Early Access game its suprisingly complete and polished.Unfortunately I did encounter some graphical issues, but I feel that is more because my computer is at the low end of the (mac) system requirements, and not because of the game. The whole game just slowed to a lag fest by the end of tutorial 4 and 5 (so much is going on, onscreen), and the text was fairly unreadable in some areas from the start. Changing the settings didn't help much and made it worse at one point. So if you are reading this for opinions on tech specs, note that game is pretty resource intensive (pun not intended) so you might want to check your system requirements are closer to the recommended than the minimum.That said, I still recommend the game! Its a great resource management game, and if you like that kind of game you will love this."
