,Recommended,271240,14494480,"Posted: 15 February, 2015",all,DarkHuD,"We're on Mars. Resources are limited, and trade is king.Who needs large armies or airforces? Not us. If we want to destroy an opponent, we can nuke their resources, buy up all their stock, or even EMP their bases.The more you play, the more you upgrade. The more you upgrade, the  more claims you have on Mars. Be warned, just because you have more claims, doesn't mean you will win. You still need to make use of those claims to the best effect. If you've gone and claimed a bunch of resource nodes, it doesn't mean you're king, without the ability to smelt things.Got that under control? But what about air, water, power, fuel? Miss out on those limited Geothermal Vents? Well instead of awesome power production, you'll be stuck with solar, which doesn't work at night, or wind, which is less than 25% as effective as the vents, when you first start out.This strategy game requires actual strategy. You can't zerg rush the enemy base and win.Conquer Mars using brains, not brawn."
,Recommended,271240,14478240,"Posted: 15 February, 2015",all,Damianll,"I do not write reviews for games.  I will also say that I quit preordering PC games due to the fact that a lot are released with many bugs (SimCity) and/or are stripped of many dynamic features of its predecessor, such as recent Civilization games.  However, I took a chance with this game as it is the first early access game that I have ever purchased.  I am shocked at the stability of the game and how much fun this game is given the fact that it is early access and within two days of release.  This game is worth the cash, especially with more on the way in regards to content.  I have only crashed once in my 14+ hours of gameplay.  Yes, there are things that could be balanced or added to increase the length of each map.  Also, I believe that the maps could be bigger, but they are nearly the perfect size for the current content.  The tutorials could use some work with directing you, but I learned quickly outside of the tutorials in the actual single-player after the AI beat me a couple of times.  Regardless, this game is extremely enjoyable, especially the single-player campaign.The single-player campaign adds a new dynamic that I find intriguing.  You are against a number of AI opponents going for different locations on a planet.  You do not face the same combination of AI opponents, usually, on the different locations.  If you win the map, then you (or the winning AI) own the map and the perks/income associated with the map are the winners to use for the next location.  Also, the remaining AI battle for some of the other locations while you are playing your map, but never more than the remaining opponents can fill up.  For instance, if there are 8 players including you, then you choose the location that you want to play.  The location can have one-three AI players (2-4, including you, of the 8 total).  This leaves 4-6 AI to battle for 2-3 of the other locations.  After every match, new locations open up.  Depending on the victory conditions (how well you win), you increase in the leaderboard of that campaign.  As you move through the campaign, you use your income to buy new engineers to enhance or unlock buildings, same for the AI winners of other maps.  Each map is different in size, terrain, rules, and some have events such as “dust storm,” which lowers the efficiency of any solar plants built on the map.This game is definitely worth buying as is and even more so knowing that the game will have more content added due to how early in the ""early access"" we are.  I highly recommend this.For those interested, I am running on:i7-4790kGTX 780 Ti16 Gigs RamWindows 8.1 Pro"
76561197992224474,Recommended,271240,14479693,"Posted: 15 February, 2015",all,Pop,Enjoyable resource management/economic RTS.Not overly complex but with enough depth to entertain for competitive multiplayer matches.Monopolies important resources and out-tech your opponents with victory seemingly coming from buying out the other players.
,Recommended,271240,14480415,"Posted: 15 February, 2015",all,zzyzx,"OTC is an interesting, if frustrating sort of economic RTS game.  Despite the fact that I have yet to actually win a skirmish vs cpu game (though, I think this is largely to do with finding my footing) it continues to draw me back in.  It feels a lot like a cross between Sid Meier's Railroads competition with a dash of Settlers of Caitan thrown in.  I found it enjoyable.There is no combat, so hostile actions are all indirect.  It's all about managing economy.This kind of game may appeal to you if you happen to like games like Banished, or any of the economy based Tycoon games."
