76561197989221215,Recommended,271240,16575053,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,Bolts,"Simple, fun and a good bite sized game. Robots are a bit overpowered though."
,Recommended,271240,14540090,"Posted: 18 February, 2015",all,KuromiAK,"With recent update, I can confidently recommend this game, but only when the game is on sale. The gameplay is interesting and I have faith in developers in delivering a decent game.In Offworld Trading Company, you play as a CEO who builds factories on the red planet. There are 4 factions to choose from, each with their unique perks. Games are mostly driven by player decisions, which makes every game unique and exciting. Even with the same map in the daily challenge, I never end up using identical strategies.With all the variety, the game is hard to master. Maximizing profit is difficult as prices depend on every player's action. It is hard to decide what to produce, even harder to predict how other players will react. There is also trade off between sabotage and development.Devs have made good progress on improving game experience and adding new content. They have fixed many bugs and improved the performance of the game. The UI now is much more informative than that at release. The update logs are long and most of the features are what players have been looking for. AI players are decent and are still being worked on. Balancing and game mechanics are also being tweaked. A big thanks to the developers.Sadly the player population is shrinking and it is hard to find a multiplayer game. Only get the game if you are fine with playing against AI players, or if you can find friends to play with. Also, despite modding being supported, I don't see active modding communities working on this game, nor is the steam workshop available.As a conclusion, the game is in good shape, and I believe it will get better. 40$ is way too much for a simple game like this, but I'd recommend people to try when the price drops below 20$."
76561197993351973,Recommended,271240,16850280,"Posted: 2 July, 2015",all,Rock,"While still in development, it does have a lot of potential. I do believe the Espionage tactics need to be a bit rarer, and there needs to be a tutorial added into the game. Over all, enjoyable, but it still needs some development.Some suggestions:Diplomacy. Not all corporate dealings are hostile.Upgrades that provide proof against certain espionage tactics. (EMP Shielding, Armed Guards, etc.)Claim purchase / upgrades. Some buildings should not require a claim.Zone of Control Limit. As of now, youcan build anywhwere on the map. Should be limited to a small area around your HQ, which then expands with HQ Upgrades. I'd also say that anything built within that zone should not require a claim for the owner, but upon purchasing stock in the owners company, allow an opponent to build within it.Different paced game modes. Some of us like to take things slow (This is why I don't to Online Strategy Games, it becomes an all out blitz). Being able to set the pace / hostility of the AI might attract more players.Solo mode - just a way to build and get familiar with the game concepts without worrying about other opponents.Over all, its nice to have a strategy game that doesn't involve blowing things up all the time or building a balanced city."
